text
@d11 7
a17 3
<p>
Astigmatism (axial): an electron-optical lens aberration that causes the defocus to be a function of azimuth, and the contrast transfer function to deviate from circular symmetry about the optical axis. As a consequence, the Thon rings deform into elliptic or hyperbolic patterns, depending on the size of defocus and the size of the astigmatic defocus difference.
<p>
d19 18
a36 10
<p>
As it is used by the Spider operations <a href="man/tfc.html">TF C</a>, <a href="man/tfct.html">TF CT</a>, <a href="man/tfd.html">TF D</a>, and <a href="man/tfed.html">TF ED</a>, astigmatism is a vector with magnitude and direction:
<p>
<b>magnitude</b>: the difference between the highest and lowest defocus.
<p>
<b>angle</b> (or azimuth): the angle of the "unaffected" axis (45 degrees between the low and high defocus axes)
<p>
By convention, this angle is clockwise from from the axis of lowest defocus. Zero degrees is defined as the center of the right hand edge of the
image.
<p>
